00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:59.180
So, before the Hollywood western, the myth of
the Frontier probably found its best expression
in Frederick Jackson Turner’s 1893 lecture,

00:00:59.180 --> 00:01:01.960
“the Significance of the Frontier in American
History.”

00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:06.040
Turner argued that the West was responsible
for key characteristics of American culture:

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:09.780
beliefs in individualism, political
democracy, and economic mobility.

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:15.680
Like, for 18th and 19th century Americans, the western frontier represented the opportunity to start over,

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:21.760
and possibly to strike it rich by dint of
one’s own individual effort, even back when
the West was, like, Ohio.

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:30.960
In this mythology, the west was a magnet for restless young men who lit out for the uncorrupted, unoccupied, untamed territories to seek their fortune.

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:37.620
But, in reality, most western settlers
went not as individuals but as members of
a family or as part of an immigrant group.

00:01:37.620 --> 00:01:42.620
And they weren’t filling up unoccupied
space either because most of that territory
was home to American Indians.

00:01:42.620 --> 00:01:49.420
Also, in addition to Easterners and migrants from
Europe, the West was settled by Chinese people and
by Mexican migrant laborers and former slaves.

00:01:49.420 --> 00:01:55.100
Plus, there were plenty of Mexicans living
there already who became Americans with
the treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.

00:01:55.100 --> 00:02:00.580
And the whole west as “a place of rugged
individualism and independence” turns out
to be an oversimplification.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:08.320
I mean, the federal government, after all, had to
pass the law that spurred homesteading, then had
to clear out American Indians already living there,

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:11.959
and had to sponsor the railroads that allowed
the West to grow in the first place.

00:02:11.959 --> 00:02:15.890
About as individualistic as the government
buying Walden Pond for Henry David Thoreau.

00:02:15.890 --> 00:02:19.880
What’s that? It’s a state park now? The
government owns it? Well, there you go.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:26.880
Now, railroads didn’t create the desire to settle
the west but they did make it possible for people who
wanted to live out west to do so, for two reasons.

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:31.480
First, without railroads there would be no
way to bring crops or other goods to market.

00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:36.740
I mean, I guess you could dig a canal
across Kansas, but, if you’ve ever been to
Kansas that is not a tantalizing proposition.

00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:42.020
Second, railroads made life in the west
profitable and livable because they brought
the goods that people needed,

00:02:42.020 --> 00:02:48.540
such as tools for planting and sowing,
shoes for wearing, books for putting on
your shelf and pretending to have read.

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:54.360
Railroads allowed settlers to stay connected
with the modernity that was becoming the hallmark
of the industrialized world in the 19th century.

00:02:54.360 --> 00:03:02.260
Now, we saw last week that the Federal government
played a key role in financing the transcontinental
railroad, but state governments got into the act too,
often to their financial detriment.

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:08.960
In fact, so many states nearly went bankrupt
financing railroads that most states now have
constitutional requirements that they balance
their budgets.

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:14.540
But perhaps the central way that the Federal
government supported the railroads, and western
settlement and investment in general,

00:03:14.540 --> 00:03:21.760
was by leading military expeditions against
American Indians, rounding them up on ever-smaller
reservations, and destroying their culture.

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:23.040
