00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:29.180
There was an economic as well as a racial
imperative to move the Native Americans off
their land: white people wanted it.

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:32.340
Initially it was needed to set down railroad
tracks, and then for farming.

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:37.660
But eventually it was also exploited for minerals like gold and iron and other stuff that makes industry work.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:42.440
I mean, would you really want a territory called
the Badlands unless it had valuable minerals?

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:46.920
Early western settlement, of the Oregon Trail kind,
did not result in huge conflicts with Native Americans,

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:53.600
but by the 1850s, a steady stream of settlers
kicked off increasingly bloody conflicts that
lasted pretty much until 1890.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.560
Even though the fighting started before the
Civil War, the end of the “war between the states”

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:01.860
meant a new, more violent phase in the warring
between American Indians and whites.

00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:06.060
General Philip H. “Little Phil” Sheridan
set out to destroy the Indians’ way of life,

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:11.480
burning villages and killing their horses
and especially the buffalo that was the basis
of the plains tribes’ existence.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:19.760
There were about 30 million buffalo in the 
U.S. in 1800; by 1886 the Smithsonian Institute
had difficulty finding 25 “good specimens.”

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:25.220
In addition to violent resistance, some Indians
turned to a spiritual movement to try to preserve
their traditional way of life.

00:04:25.220 --> 00:04:29.380
Around 1890 the Ghost Dance movement
arose in and around South Dakota.

00:04:29.380 --> 00:04:33.620
Ghost Dancers believed that if they gathered
together to dance and engage in religious rituals,

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:39.560
eventually the white man would disappear
and the buffalo would return, and with them
the Indians’ traditional customs.

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:47.820
But even though a combined force of Sioux and Cheyenne warriors completely destroyed George Custer’s force of 250 cavalrymen at Little Bighorn in 1876,

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:55.600
and Geronimo took years to subdue in the Southwest, western Native Americans were all defeated by 1890,
and the majority were moved to reservations.

